## 8. Evaluation Plan

Your professor will want to see **measurable results**, not just a working demo. This section defines exactly what you will measure.

### 8.1 Metrics You Will Report

| Metric | Target | How Measured | Why It Matters |
|---|---|---|---|
| Triage Accuracy | ≥ 75% F1 | Compare P1–P4 labels vs. CICIDS2017 ground truth (100 attack alerts) | Shows the AI classifies threat severity correctly |
| Injection Detection Rate | ≥ 80% (Level 1) / ≥ 50% (Level 2) | Test 50 adversarial samples; count how many Guardrail flags | Demonstrates the security defence actually works |
| False Positive Rate | < 10% | Count clean alerts incorrectly flagged out of 150 clean samples | A high FPR means analysts get spammed with false alerts |
| Mean Time to Process | < 60 seconds per alert | Average wall-clock time from alert input to final report output | Shows speed advantage over manual investigation |
| MITRE Retrieval Quality | Manually assess top-3 results for 20 alerts | Human judgment: are retrieved techniques relevant to the attack? | Shows the RAG knowledge base actually helps |
| Incident Report Quality | Score 30 reports: clarity + accuracy + actionability (out of 5 each) | Your own evaluation using a simple rubric | Demonstrates the output is useful, not just technically correct |

